messages.name: Lithquack Haderach (-$77.02)
messages.text:
Here's the argument that my $15 loss tonight had a sizable amount to do with luck. On average, a player would expect to get hands in the following categories at the corresponding rate:

Suited hands: 23.53%
Pocket pairs: 5.88%
Pocket face cards (including tens): 14.33%

I got hands tonight in those categories at these rates:

Suited hands: 16.25%
Pocket pairs: 2.50%
Pocket face cards (including tens): 12.50%

messages.name: Lithquack Haderach (-$77.02)
messages.text:
Here's a fun thing based on my position play. On average every hand tonight (I played 80 hands total), I lose the following amount of money in each position group:

SB: $0.01
BB: $0.01
Early: $0.64
Middle: $0.10
Late: $0.04

This tells me I'm playing way too many hands from the early position, or staying in way too long

messages.name: Lithquack Haderach (-$77.02)
messages.text: Ok starting to do some advanced analytics on my poker play to determine where my weaknesses are and how much has to do with luck

messages.text: Happy to discuss this more tonight, but for those of you interested in a Pokersters fantasy football league — any interest in setting up a dynasty league? Basically, instead of drafting entirely new rosters each year, your roster carries over season to season and we draft that year’s rookies. tldr tropical island theme but the twist is the island natives deify @Mark Fowler (-$23.32) 

Isle of Mark Night (2021)

After several minutes of walking, we arrive at their village. At the center of the village sits a towering figure whose face is hidden in shadows. Upon seeing the sorry state of our party, the leader turns to us, and we see the shape of a great beard emerge.

We're having a great time sailing through the Carribean, when suddenly we run into some foul weather. A cyclone strikes the ship, and we all narrowly escape and wash up onto a deserted island. We quickly encounter the natives, who bind us with rope and take us to to see their leader. The whole time, we overhear mutterings about a variety of topics: the ripeness of the pocket pair? how interesting the weather patterns were the night before?? and how they need to make more salve to soothe an aching back???

picture this:

13 years from now, we've embarked on the Pokersters annual cruise. Almost everyone is able to attend, one person has mysteriously dissapeared.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text: I, 3 weeks ago (a reasonable window of time to get back to the store for a refund) bought a $7 bag of asparagus. The next day, Selena opens the bag and recoils at the rotting scent, and I throw the package away so as to not spoil the smell of my fridge or apartment. No other refrigerated item from the purchase was bad, so I reasonably determine the asparagus was bad from the start, not because of some error on my part. I return to Costco and ask for my money back from a defective product they sold me. When they ask if I brought it with me, I incredulously say no, because why would I carry around a 3 week old bag of spoiled asparagus. They give me a persnickety response and smartly say I should’ve taken a picture for proof, as if I (a loyal customer who spends several hundreds of dollars at Costco every year) am trying to rip off a multi-billion dollar company $7 for asparagus.

messages.text: This is a very biased recounting of the facts. Let’s try my version
